node.text:
A friend reached out to me a few weeks ago expressing that he could not find a reason to forgive himself. I’ve been there: that deep ditch of insecurities and personal accusations is a monster of a climb. 

After praying, reading Quran and thinking on Allah’s ﷻ names, I wrote back to him a week or so later. Here js a part that, while writing to him, I found myself moved because it spoke to me directly:

The Irrationality Of Allah’s Grace & Forgiveness 

You rationalizing the magnitude of your sins suffocates thoughts of your eligibility for redemption and clemency. Yet, faith reminds you that God’s mercy, from our limited perspective, is irrational. “God forgives all sins: every one of them.” Quran 39:53. And it is there, in your lowest moment, touched by an unexplainable, irrational grace, that your hope is lifted.

Abu Dhar رضي الله عنه said that the Prophet ﷺ said, 

“No slave of Allah says lailaha ila Allah, and later he dies upon that (conviction) except that person will enter paradise.” 

Abu Dhar رضي الله عنه asked, “Even if they murder or fornicate?” The Prophet ﷺ replied, “Even if they murder or fornicate.” Sahih al-Bukhari 

Allah ﷻ mentions a hosts of sins in the 25th chapter of the Quran. And, after threatening those who commit them says, 

“Except for those who repent, and believe, and do good deeds. These—God will replace their bad deeds with good deeds. God is ever Forgiving and Merciful.” Quran 25:70

So, not only is there grace. There is an exchange of evil for good that defies our logic of benevolence, forgiveness, pardon and justice. Our mercy has limits, even with those who make amends. Allah is different. Whoever sincerely repents, there is hope. 

“Repentance is available from God for those who commit evil out of ignorance, and then repent soon after. God will relent towards them.” Quran 4:17

Why you find no reason to forgive yourself, know that faith and dedication to being better are keys to a flood of forgiveness. And by default, the harshness, brutality and love to destroy ourselves and others rests in our notions of “rational forgiveness.” “He has no likeness.” Quran 112:4 

Make sure to repent and live right. That is all He commands.

node.text:
Families across Afghanistan are asking for our attention and compassion right now: An estimated 270,000 Afghans have been newly displaced inside the country since January 2021—primarily due to insecurity and violence—bringing the total uprooted population to more than 3.5 million people. Families are forced to flee their homes in recent weeks have cited the worsening security situation as the predominant reason for their flight.

All this as Afghanistan sits on the brink of famine. This June, Afghanistan officially fell into drought, making rough conditions even worse: “The drought has also exacerbated the hard living conditions in a country that is grappling with escalating conflict, COVID-19, and crippling poverty. COVID-19 cases have steadily risen since mid-May 2021, with compounding socioeconomic impacts,” according to ReliefWeb. And now, more and more of the country has been moving into crisis mode with regard to food insecurity.

Basic living standards in Afghanistan are among the lowest in the world. Yet experts stress that the latest poverty numbers should serve as a call to action, not a reason for despair:

9.4 million people require humanitarian and protection assistance (ReliefWeb, 2020)
Afghanistan is experiencing stagnating economic growth (World Bank)

Escalation of violence, loss of essential livelihood, and little to no access to basic services are major concerns (Relief Lab)

The country and its people are also adversely affected by global warming: Research suggests that climate issues, like drought, is alarmingly linked to changes in climate. Many displaced families lost all crops and livestock, and struggled to survive cold winters in makeshift tents.

With all this considered, one thing remains clear: The people of Afghanistan are resilient and, with the support of donors like you, families in need there can access opportunities to break the chains of poverty and move toward success.

For more information visit @islamicreliefusa
